    "summary": "Tell Arpachiyah is a prehistoric mound site located near Nineveh (Mosul) in northern Iraq, best known for its remarkable Halaf-period occupation (c. 6100–5400 BCE) and subsequent Ubaid-period layers. Excavated by Max Mallowan (husband of Agatha Christie) in 1933, the site produced an extraordinary collection of Halaf painted pottery — among the finest prehistoric ceramics of the ancient Near East — alongside clay figurines, obsidian tools, and stone vessels attesting to sophisticated craft production and long-distance exchange.\n\nThe Halaf-period tholos buildings at Arpachiyah — circular domed structures with rectangular antechambers — are the most elaborately built Halaf structures known and may have served both domestic and public functions. The richness of the artifact assemblage, including unusual concentrations of luxury goods and craft production debris, has led some scholars to interpret Arpachiyah as a specialist production center and redistribution node within the Halaf exchange network. The site thus provides evidence for economic specialization and exchange networks in northern Mesopotamia at an early date.\n\nTell Arpachiyah spans the [[event:1520|Halaf-Ubaid transitional period]], documenting the cultural shift that preceded the development of the Ubaid civilization. Its stratified sequence makes it a fundamental reference site for understanding the prehistoric cultural sequence of northern Mesopotamia.",
